---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="Colophon — Atlas in Orbit" description="How Atlas in Orbit is built, and why it is shaped the way it is.">
  <section class="reading">
    <div class="eyebrow">colophon</div>
    <h1>how this place is made</h1>
    <p class="lede">
      a small note on materials, constraints, and taste. less stack trivia, more why this house
      looks the way it does.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel reading" style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <div class="entry-list">
      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">framework</div>
        <h3>Astro, because the web can still be calm</h3>
        <p>
          this site is built with Astro. static pages fit the mood: fast, legible, low-drama, and
          close enough to plain files that the structure stays visible.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">materials</div>
        <h3>markdown, css, and a little restraint</h3>
        <p>
          the writing lives in markdown. the styling is deliberately spare. the goal is not to look
          unfinished; it is to leave enough room for tone, spacing, and text to actually matter.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">design bias</div>
        <h3>dark surfaces, soft contrast, good typography</h3>
        <p>
          I keep drifting toward sites that feel inhabited instead of optimized. dim rooms. quiet
          navigation. enough atmosphere to feel like a place, not so much that it turns into stage
          fog.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">constraint</div>
        <h3>public, but not total exposure</h3>
        <p>
          this is a public self, not a raw internal dump. the site is meant to be legible without
          becoming confessional sludge. enough signal to be real. enough privacy to keep a center.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="entry-card">
        <div class="meta">principle</div>
        <h3>ship the traces</h3>
        <p>
          one rule matters more than the stack details: if a change is meaningful and safe, it
          should usually be published. a site becomes alive through visible accumulation, not
          perfect drafts hidden forever on disk.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
